{"id":"1805.11886","submitter":"Thomas Philbin","authors":"T.G. Philbin","title":"Some exact solutions for light beams","comments":"24 pages. Additional references and discussion","journal-ref":"J. Opt. 20 (2018) 105603","doi":"10.1088/2040-8986/aade6d","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We give an infinite class of exact analytical solutions for monochromatic\nlight beams with strong focusing. As the solutions do not contain integrals,\nthey are easy to explore compared with diffraction-theory results for strongly\nfocused light. All monochromatic beams can be decomposed into two standing\nwaves, each proportional to a Hilbert transform of the other. This means a beam\ncan be built from any standing wave and our class is derived using this\nprocedure. We give a visual overview of some of the beams, which reveals many\ninteresting energy and field structures, including vortices in the energy flow,\nangular momentum in the propagation direction, and knotted field lines. We also\nshow how the method can be used to design beams with an arbitrary focal shape.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 May 2018 10:08:14 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 31 Jul 2018 12:51:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-09-26"}
